    "markdown": "## Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan Overview\n\n### Why local patients choose Cadabams Diagnostics\n- 25+ years of trusted imaging in South India\n- Color & spectral Doppler on every scan at no extra cost\n- Reports released within 3 hours; digital copies sent instantly\n- Online booking, walk-ins and home-collection of bloods if needed\n### What to expect on test day in 60 seconds\n1. Check-in at reception (5 min)\n2. Change into a gown if required (2 min)\n3. Lie on the scan table; warm gel applied (1 min)\n4. Transducer glides across abdomen capturing images (15–20 min)\n5. Wipe off gel, get dressed, receive provisional findings (2 min)\n---\n## Types of Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n- \\*\\*Color Doppler:\\*\\* Visual overview of vessel direction and turbulence.\n- \\*\\*Spectral Doppler:\\*\\* Numerical speed and resistance patterns.\n- \\*\\*Power Doppler:\\*\\* Higher sensitivity for very slow or small-volume flow—ideal for tiny renal vessels.\n---\n\n## When and Who Needs to Take an Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan?\n\n### Symptoms that trigger referral\n- Unexplained abdominal pain or swelling\n- Sudden weight loss or jaundice\n- Persistent nausea after fatty meals\n- High blood pressure that’s hard to control\n### Age groups & risk profiles\n- Adults 40+ with diabetes or hypertension\n- Children with inherited liver disorders\n- Pregnant women with suspected portal hypertension\n- Post-kidney-transplant patients for routine graft monitoring\n---\n\n## Risks & Limitations of the Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n### Safety profile (zero radiation)\n- Uses harmless sound waves—no ionising radiation, safe for children and expectant mothers.\n### Limitations in obese patients or excessive bowel gas\n- Body fat or gas can scatter sound waves, occasionally limiting view depth. In such cases Cadabams Diagnostics may suggest a brief repeat after bowel prep or low-dose CT if clinically justified.\n---\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During the Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n| Parameter | What We Measure |\n|-----------|-----------------|\n| Portal vein flow velocity | Speed of blood entering the liver |\n| Hepatic artery resistive index | Resistance to flow; rises in cirrhosis |\n| Renal artery peak systolic velocity | Indicator of possible renal artery stenosis |\n---\n\n## Reasons for Taking an Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n- Evaluate abdominal pain or swelling of unknown cause\n- Monitor liver cirrhosis and varices\n- Assess kidney transplant perfusion and early rejection signs\n- Detect narrowing of renal or mesenteric arteries before surgery\n---\n\n## Benefits of Taking the Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n- \\*\\*Non-invasive procedure\\*\\*—no needles, no contrast\n- \\*\\*No sedation required\\*\\*—drive home immediately\n- \\*\\*Real-time blood-flow imaging\\*\\*—results shared with you on the spot\n---\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n- \\*\\*Portal hypertension\\*\\*—high pressure in liver veins\n- \\*\\*Renal artery stenosis\\*\\*—narrowing that causes resistant hypertension\n- \\*\\*Budd-Chiari syndrome\\*\\*—blocked hepatic veins\n- \\*\\*Hepatic artery thrombosis\\*\\*—post-transplant emergency\n- \\*\\*Abdominal aortic aneurysm with turbulent flow\\*\\*\n---\n\n## Preparing for Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n\n### Fasting instructions (6–8 hrs)\n- Only water allowed; skip breakfast for morning slots.\n- Continue essential medicines with a small sip of water.\n### Medication guidelines\n- Avoid gas-forming tablets the night before.\n- If on anticoagulants, bring your latest INR/PT reports.\n---\n## Pre-requisites Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n- Valid doctor prescription (hard copy or digital)\n- Recent blood reports if on anticoagulants or have clotting disorders\n- Comfortable, two-piece clothing recommended\n---\n## Best Time to Take the Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n- \\*\\*Morning slots after overnight fast\\*\\* give the clearest images.\n- Avoid booking immediately after lunch or carbonated drinks.\n---\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*Adults & children\\*\\*—no lower age limit\n- \\*\\*Pregnancy-safe imaging\\*\\*—no radiation, no contrast\n- Patients with implanted devices (e.g., insulin pumps) can undergo scan; just inform staff beforehand.\n---\n## Procedure for Taking an Abdomen Doppler Ultrasound Scan\n1. \\*\\*Check-in & paperwork\\*\\*—verify ID, consent and fasting status.\n2. \\*\\*Positioning\\*\\*—lie flat on the scan table, abdomen exposed.\n3. \\*\\*Gel application & transducer movement\\*\\*—cool, water-based gel improves sound transmission; gentle pressure captures images and Doppler waveforms.\n4. \\*\\*Real-time review\\*\\*—sonographer explains key findings before you leave.\n5. \\*\\*Clean-up & digital report\\*\\*—receive link to download images and report.\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- \\*\\*Inform about implanted devices\\*\\*—pacemakers, pumps or metal clips.\n- \\*\\*Mention contrast allergy history\\*\\*—though none is used, it helps us note your overall allergy profile.\n---"
